{
  "title": "Feng: The 19-Year-Old Producer Who Stopped Asking",
  "category": "music",
  "author": "Allastair Voss",
  "date": "2026-04-25",
  "image": "/assets/images/artists/feng.jpg",
  "body": "Travas Alan Feneley is nineteen and from Croydon, which is a sentence the UK rap scene has been waiting on for about three years without realising it. He produces everything himself. He raps over it. He calls the project Feng and the whole thing has the feel of a kid who never stopped to wonder whether he was allowed to do this.\n\n[spotify:artist/278vNvolx8H3sQJ2hgOMnh]\n\nHis debut mixtape WHAT THE FENG dropped in February 2025. The track everyone latched onto was \"who do u wanna be\" — a piece of self-produced, self-rapped, self-everything writing that addresses an entire generation of bedroom-rotting teenagers and dares them to do something about it. The FADER put it on their best-of-2025. COMPLEX wrote about him. The clips made the rounds. None of that made him slow down.\n\n## The Sound\n\n[img:/assets/images/artists/feng-weekend-rockstar-croydon.jpg]\n\nWhat he is doing is not exactly UK rap and not exactly indie. \"New grime\" pulls the title genre into a brighter register. \"Primrose Hill\" sounds like a London afternoon you nearly missed. \"Damn phone\" is the kind of track where the production is doing something specific the lyrics already know about. \"Devil horns and a halo\" is the most punk thing on streaming services right now made by someone who has never picked up a guitar.\n\nFeng's production has a quality that is harder to achieve than it sounds: it is energetic without being cluttered. Every element has room. The drums hit with the precision of someone who has spent years listening to what makes a beat land, and the melodic choices sit in a zone between post-punk guitar textures and synth-led UK pop that has no obvious predecessor. He is not combining two genres so much as treating his influences as raw materials that have no obligation to remain recognizable.\n\nThe lyrics operate at the same register as the production — direct without being blunt, personal without being confessional. \"who do u wanna be\" works because it doesn't answer its own question. It poses the problem and leaves the room. That restraint is the mark of a writer who trusts the listener, which is rarer in artists of any age, let alone nineteen.\n\n## Where Croydon Fits\n\nCroydon has produced a particular strain of UK artist: self-sufficient, slightly outside the London music industry's center of gravity, inclined toward building entire worlds rather than pitching individual songs. MOVELLAS, Stormzy's earliest work, the south London drill scene's geographic spread — Croydon sits at the edge of all of these but is not fully claimed by any of them. That position creates its own aesthetic freedom.\n\nFeng operates with the self-sufficiency of someone who built his practice without waiting for institutional support. Everything self-produced, everything self-released, everything on his own terms. The FADER attention and the COMPLEX coverage are consequences of the music, not prerequisites for it. The work came first. The infrastructure followed.\n\nThe self-sufficiency that Croydon produces has a particular character: artists who have no interest in chasing industry attention because they built their practice entirely in its absence. By the time the FADER piece ran, Feng already had a full album concept, multiple completed singles, and a clear sense of what WEEKEND ROCKSTAR should be. The coverage did not begin his career. It arrived in the middle of it.\n\n## Nine Years of Self-Teaching\n\nFeneley has been producing music in FL Studio since he was ten years old. Nine years of daily production practice before a single song reached an external audience. Without formal tuition, without music theory courses, without the implicit conservatism that structured education tends to instill. When you learn a production program that young and that independently, you build habits that formal training typically discourages.\n\nThe aesthetic choices on WHAT THE FENG are not the choices of someone who learned the rules and then broke them. They are the choices of someone who never encountered those rules as rules. This is audible. The arrangements do things that a producer trained in UK rap convention would be unlikely to attempt, not because the conventions are enforced, but because they form an invisible ceiling. Feneley built without that ceiling. He has been constructing his own approach from the floor up since he was a child.\n\nThis produces music that resists description through reference. The influences are audible, but the application is too specific to his own taste for the music to sit comfortably inside any of its sources. It absorbs and transforms rather than quotes. The result is genuinely its own thing. Nine years of practice without external correction produces an artist who sees possibility where trained producers see constraint. WHAT THE FENG is the first sustained document of that practice reaching an audience. WEEKEND ROCKSTAR will be the second, and the distance between them will show what nine years of uninterrupted practice produces when it finally has a full album's worth of space to operate in. That distance is worth paying attention to.\n\n## What's Coming\n\nThe debut album, WEEKEND ROCKSTAR, is cued up. \"Cali Crazy\" was the first single and it sounds like it. It was written by a teenager landing in Los Angeles for the first time, which it is, with all the disorientation and hunger that implies. \"Coming of age\" hints at where the album might land emotionally. The bigger picture is becoming visible.\n\nThe album title is both description and aspiration: the weekend rockstar is someone who lives an ordinary life during the week and transforms at the weekend, who carries a version of themselves that the ordinary world doesn't fully see. That duality runs through the music, the tension between the Croydon teenager and the artist building something that reaches beyond that geography.\n\nFeng is making a strong case for the proposition that the most interesting UK rap right now is being self-produced by people too young to have learned what they're not supposed to do. Listen to \"who do u wanna be\" first. Then everything else.\n\nThe output already exists. The audience is already there. The album will confirm both, and then some.\n\n[download:/assets/images/artists/feng-weekend-rockstar-croydon-social-9x16.jpg|Download Social Card]",
  "description": "Travas Alan Feneley is nineteen and from Croydon, which is a sentence the UK rap scene has been waiting on for about three years without realising it. He",
  "image_alt": "Feng: The 19-Year-Old Producer Who Stopped Asking"
}
