# ---- kelsey-lu-so-help-me-god ----
echo 'Writing: kelsey-lu-so-help-me-god'
cat > ~/artonly.io/posts/kelsey-lu-so-help-me-god.json << 'POSTEOF_KELSEY_LU_SO_HELP_ME_GOD'
{
  "slug": "kelsey-lu-so-help-me-god",
  "title": "Kelsey Lu Took Seven Years to Make Her Second Album and Every Day of It Shows",
  "subtitle": "So Help Me God arrives this June with Sampha, Kamasi Washington, and Kim Gordon in tow -- and a vision that refuses to explain itself.",
  "author": "Leelou Blanc",
  "date": "2026-04-12",
  "category": "music",
  "tags": [
    "Kelsey Lu",
    "art pop",
    "Dirty Hit",
    "Jack Antonoff",
    "Sampha",
    "cello"
  ],
  "image": "/assets/images/artists/kelsey-lu-so-help-me-god-main.jpg",
  "image_position": "center 30%",
  "body": "[spotify:track/3TcuyO1stSlzxMQRb14M16]\n\nSeven years is a long time to disappear. For most artists, it is career death, the algorithm forgets, the press cycle moves on, and whatever goodwill existed evaporates into the feed. Kelsey Lu released Blood in 2019, scored a Celine Sciamma film, contributed to projects by Solange and Skrillex, and then went quiet. Not silent, she was composing the score for Savanah Leaf's Earth Mama, building a visual language, and apparently writing a record that features Sampha, Kamasi Washington, and Kim Gordon. The kind of guest list that does not arrive by accident.\n\nSo Help Me God is due June 12 on Dirty Hit. It is ten tracks. It is co-produced by Lu, Jack Antonoff, and Yves Rothman. And if the first two singles are any indication, it is a record that refuses to make its audience comfortable.\n\n[youtube:yMVnh3O6cLQ]\n\n## The Architecture of Devotion\n\n\"Portrait of a Lady on Fire\", the second single, dropped April 9, is named after the Sciamma film, and the connection is not decorative. The song is a cello-embellished synth ballad built on a sinuous, capricious vocal melody. \"Do you ever get like this, I wonder?\" Lu repeats, mapping the vertigo of early intimacy with a precision that most love songs never attempt. The cello does not just add texture. It functions as a second voice, a counterpoint that holds the emotional register Lu's vocals are too restrained to carry alone.\n\nThe first single, \"Running to Pain,\" arrived in late 2025 with a Savanah Leaf-directed video that Spotify featured in its Directed By series. The track leans harder into tension and release, the kind of push-pull that characterizes music made by someone who knows exactly how much to withhold. Lu's vision, according to Leaf, was \"a dark fairytale styling anchored by the raw honesty of the lyrics.\" That description maps cleanly onto the entire project.\n\n## The Guest List as Architecture\n\nThe collaborators on So Help Me God deserve scrutiny. Sampha, who took five years between his own first and second albums, brings a sensibility attuned to grief and transcendence. His presence suggests the record will go to emotional places that require a particular kind of witness. Kamasi Washington brings the spiritual jazz weight that Lu's cello work has always orbited. Kim Gordon brings noise, texture, and the specific authority of someone who has spent four decades refusing to be domesticated by genre.\n\nAntonoff, for all his ubiquity, has proven himself capable of restraint when the artist demands it. The records where he has served the artist rather than imposed his own sonic signature, Lana Del Rey's Norman Fucking Rockwell, Lorde's Melodrama, are his best work. The question with So Help Me God is whether Lu's vision is strong enough to keep Antonoff's instincts in service rather than in charge. The singles suggest it is.\n\nThis is not a committee record. These collaborators suggest a specific intention: to make something that moves between shadow and release, devotion and dissonance, without ever settling into a single register. The tracklist, \"Reaper,\" \"Comfort,\" \"American Sonnet,\" \"Cutting Off the Head of a Ghost\", reads more like a poetry collection than an album sequence.\n\n## The Cello as Core Instrument\n\nLu trained as a classical cellist before moving toward song. That background shows not just in the way the cello appears on her recordings but in the way she constructs melodic lines and thinks about the relationship between harmony and time. Her voice and cello often occupy the same emotional register simultaneously, which is unusual. Most artists use orchestral instruments as a contrast or a wash. Lu uses the cello as an extension of the voice, or the voice as an extension of the cello, and the two become difficult to separate.\n\nBlood demonstrated this but So Help Me God, from the singles, takes it further. The cello in \"Portrait of a Lady on Fire\" is not an arrangement choice. It is a structural element. Remove it and the song changes its meaning, not just its texture.\n\n## Film and Score Work as Preparation\n\nThe years between Blood and So Help Me God were not empty. Earth Mama, Savanah Leaf's debut feature, needed a score that could hold its emotional register without pushing. Film scoring disciplines a composer in ways that album-making does not. You learn to serve something outside yourself. You learn economy, the art of making a small gesture carry large emotional weight. You learn to work in someone else's time signature.\n\nThat discipline is audible in the singles. There is no wasted motion. Nothing is there to impress. Everything is there because it is needed. Seven years of this kind of thinking produces music that is structurally lean in a way that Blood, for all its beauty, was not quite.\n\n## The Seven-Year Silence and What It Built\n\nThe question that haunts long absences is whether the music that emerges justifies them. The answer is not always yes. Some artists disappear and return with something smaller than what they left behind, the absence having served entropy rather than development. So Help Me God does not have that quality. It sounds like the product of sustained purposeful work across seven years, not like music made in spite of the gap.\n\nLu's score for Earth Mama is the most useful document for understanding what changed. Savanah Leaf's film, set in the California foster care system, attentive to Black maternal experience, required a sonic approach that served the human weight of the subject without overwhelming it. What Lu learned from that work is audible in the album singles: economy, the art of the musical gesture that says everything by not saying more, the restraint that comes from working in service of something larger than a single song.\n\nJack Antonoff's involvement generated predictable skepticism. He is on so many major records that his presence can feel like a genre designation rather than a creative contribution. The evidence from \"Portrait of a Lady on Fire\" and \"Running to Pain\" suggests Lu used him as a specific tool rather than a signature. The sonics are hers. The decisions are hers. Antonoff's fingerprints, usually vivid, are subdued to the point of disappearance. That is either the sign of a producer working at the top of his craft or an artist who simply insisted.\n\n## The Performance as Proof\n\nLu is playing Blue Note in New York on April 16 and 17, and Blue Note in Los Angeles on April 25 and 26. These are not arenas. They are rooms designed for proximity, for the kind of listening that demands you stop scrolling and sit with what is in front of you. In May, she will present PENUMBRA at Palazzo Diedo in Venice, a large-scale performance work commissioned by Olivier Berggruen that blurs the lines between concert, installation, and ritual.\n\nThat trajectory, from intimate club shows to a Venice palazzo commission in the span of a month, tells you everything about where Kelsey Lu sees herself. She is not chasing the market. She is building a world. Whether the rest of us are ready for it is, characteristically, not her concern.\n\n[download:/assets/images/artists/kelsey-lu-so-help-me-god-social-9x16.jpg|Download Social Card]",
  "description": "Seven years is a long time to disappear. For most artists, it is career death -- the algorithm forgets, the press cycle moves on, and whatever goodwill",
  "image_alt": "Kelsey Lu Took Seven Years to Make Her Second Album and Every Day of It Shows"
}
POSTEOF_KELSEY_LU_SO_HELP_ME_GOD

# ---- kendrick-lamar-gnx-hip-hop-culture-2025 ----
echo 'Writing: kendrick-lamar-gnx-hip-hop-culture-2025'
